[src:kubernetes-pod-security/microservices] With microservices, only the microservice supporting the function with resource constraints needs to be scaled out, thus providing resource and cost optimization benefits.
[src:kubernetes-pod-security/microservices] Despite its benefits, microservices architecture introduces challenges such as increased operational complexity, network latency, and the need for robust monitoring and fault tolerance mechanisms.
[src:kubernetes-pod-security/microservices] Cell-based architecture is a distributed computing design in which computational resources are organized into self-contained units called cells.
[src:kubernetes-pod-security/microservices] Each cell operates independently, handling a subset of requests while maintaining scalability, fault isolation, and availability.
[src:kubernetes-pod-security/microservices] A cell typically consists of multiple microservices and functions as an autonomous unit.
[src:kubernetes-pod-security/microservices] In some implementations, entire sets of microservices are replicated across multiple cells, enabling requests to be rerouted to another operational cell if one experiences a failure.
[src:kubernetes-pod-security/microservices] This approach is intended to improve system-wide resilience by limiting the impact of localized failures.
[src:kubernetes-pod-security/microservices] Some implementations incorporate circuit breakers within and between cells.
[src:kubernetes-pod-security/microservices] Within a cell, circuit breakers may be used to mitigate cascading failures among microservices, while inter-cell circuit breakers can isolate failing cells and redirect traffic to those that remain operational.
[src:kubernetes-pod-security/microservices] Cell-based architecture has been adopted in certain large-scale distributed systems where fault isolation and redundancy are design priorities.
[src:kubernetes-pod-security/microservices] Its implementation varies based on system requirements, infrastructure constraints, and specific operational goals.
