[src:kubernetes-pod-security/role-based-access-control] In information security, **role-based access control** (**RBAC**) or **role-based security** is an approach to restricting system access to authorized users.
[src:kubernetes-pod-security/role-based-access-control] It is a policy-neutral computer access control mechanism defined around roles and privileges.
[src:kubernetes-pod-security/role-based-access-control] The components of RBAC, such as role-permissions, user-role and role-role relationships, make it simple to perform user assignments.
[src:kubernetes-pod-security/role-based-access-control] RBAC can be used to facilitate administration of security in large organizations with hundreds of users and thousands of permissions.
[src:kubernetes-pod-security/role-based-access-control] Although RBAC is different from mandatory access control and discretionary access control (DAC) frameworks, it can enforce these policies.
[src:kubernetes-pod-security/role-based-access-control] Its approach is also different from context-based access control and access-control lists.
